      "content": "Yes, that distinction is often how judges frame the difference between rehabilitative and punitive measures. Case A’s established stability makes them a prime candidate for a lenient sentence, as the system perceives little risk of relapse. Conversely, Case B's instability signals a higher perceived need for external control, making intensive supervision or time in custody seem more appropriate to break cycles of potential criminality. This reflects the legal tendency to treat pre-existing stability as a protective factor, while instability requires correctional intervention.",
